⚠️ 15. Pass by value vs reference
<?php

// pass by value
function test1($x) {
    $x = 20;
}

$a = 10;
test1($a);
echo $a; // unchanged

echo "<br>";

// pass by reference
function test2(&$x) {
    $x = 20;
}

$b = 10;
test2($b);
echo $b; // changed

?>

🧠 Explanation:

Value → copy (no change)
Reference → original changes

📤 Output:

10
20



1. Difference between GET and POST (very important)
🔹 GET

👉 Data is sent in the URL

Example:

index.php?name=John&age=20
Characteristics:
Data is visible
Limited size
Can be bookmarked
Less secure
Used for:
Search
Filters
Simple requests
🔹 POST

👉 Data is sent hidden in request body (not in URL)

Characteristics:
Not visible in URL
Larger data allowed
More secure than GET (but NOT fully secure)
Cannot be bookmarked
Used for:
Login forms
Registration
Sending sensitive data
🎯 Interview one-liner:

👉 “GET is used for retrieving data and is visible in the URL, while POST is used for sending data securely and is not visible in the URL.”

✔ 2. What is $_GET and $_POST?

These are called superglobal variables in PHP.

👉 Meaning: they are available everywhere in your code.

🔹 $_GET

Used to collect data sent via GET

$name = $_GET['name'];
🔹 $_POST

Used to collect data sent via POST

$name = $_POST['name'];
🔑 Important idea:

The input field name becomes the key

<input name="email">
$_POST['email']
✔ 3. What is Validation?

👉 Validation = checking if input is correct and acceptable

Examples:
❌ Invalid:
Empty name
Email without "@"
Password too short
Example code:
if (empty($_POST['name'])) {
    echo "Name is required";
}
Types of validation:
Required fields
Email format
Number check
Length check
🎯 Interview line:

👉 “Validation ensures the data is correct before processing.”

✔ 4. What is Sanitization? (THIS is where you were confused)

Let’s clear it properly.

👉 Definition:

Sanitization = cleaning user input to make it safe

❗ Why?

Users (or hackers) can send dangerous input like:

<script>alert("hack")</script>

If you display it directly → it runs as code.

🔹 htmlspecialchars() (most common)
$name = htmlspecialchars($_POST['name']);
What it does:

Converts special characters:

< → &lt;
> → &gt;

So browser shows text instead of executing it.

🔹 Are there other sanitization methods? YES
1. trim()

Removes extra spaces

$name = trim($_POST['name']);
2. filter_var()

Used for specific data types

$email = filter_var($_POST['email'], FILTER_SANITIZE_EMAIL);
3. mysqli_real_escape_string() (for database)

Prevents SQL injection

🔑 Important concept:

👉 Sanitization depends on where data will be used

Usage	Method
Display in HTML	htmlspecialchars()
Email	filter_var()
Database	prepared statements / escaping
🎯 Interview line:

👉 “Sanitization cleans input to prevent malicious code execution.”

✔ 5. Why Security Matters

If you don’t secure form input:

❌ Risks:
Hackers inject scripts (XSS)
Database attacks (SQL injection)
Steal user data
Example attack:
<script>document.cookie</script>

👉 Can steal session data

🔐 Basic protections:
Validation
Sanitization
Use POST for sensitive data
Use prepared statements (DB)
🎯 Interview line:

👉 “Security prevents unauthorized access and protects user data.”

✔ 6. What action and method do
🔹 method

Defines how data is sent

method="POST"
🔹 action

Defines where data goes

action="process.php"

👉 If empty:

action=""

→ submits to same page

🧪 7. FULL Example (index.php)

This is what interviewers LOVE.

📄 index.php
<?php
// Check if form is submitted
if ($_SERVER["REQUEST_METHOD"] == "POST") {

    // Get and sanitize input
    $name = htmlspecialchars(trim($_POST['name']));

    // Validation
    if (empty($name)) {
        $message = "Name is required";
    } else {
        $message = "Hello, " . $name;
    }
}
?>

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Form Example</title>
</head>
<body>

<h2>Simple Form</h2>

<form method="POST" action="">
    Name: <input type="text" name="name">
    <input type="submit" value="Submit">
</form>

<?php
// Show message
if (!empty($message)) {
    echo "<p>$message</p>";
}
?>

</body>
</html>
🔍 Step-by-step flow:
User enters name
Clicks submit
Page reloads

PHP checks:

$_SERVER["REQUEST_METHOD"] == "POST"

Gets data:

$_POST['name']

Cleans it:

trim() + htmlspecialchars()
Validates
Displays result
🧠 Final Interview Summary (quick revision)
GET → visible, less secure
POST → hidden, more secure
$_GET, $_POST → collect form data
Validation → check correctness
Sanitization → clean harmful input
Security → prevent attacks
method → how data is sent
action → where data goes
